<Base title="FAQ" description="Frequently asked questions about cadence.">
  <h1>FAQ</h1>

  <h2>Is cadence stable for production use?</h2>
  <p>
    Cadence is at v0.8. The CLI surface and config schema are stable for
    everyday use; v1.0 will lock semver on the schema. Production users
    should be comfortable with minor schema migrations between 0.x bumps.
  </p>

  <h2>How does cadence compare to shadcn?</h2>
  <p>
    Cadence and shadcn share a model: <em>framework + opinionated content,
    scaffolded into your repo, owned by you</em>. Cadence is for codebase
    automation (audits, standards, scaffolds, AI bridges); shadcn is for
    UI components. The upgrade story differs: cadence ships a real three-
    way merge in <code>cadence upgrade</code> so you can pull in framework
    improvements; shadcn punts on upgrades.
  </p>

  <h2>Why "cadence"?</h2>
  <p>
    "The rhythm of repeatable patterns; standards become the system's
    heartbeat." Names matching the editorial-portfolio convention
    (Blaze, Chorus, Substrate) ship best alongside their siblings.
  </p>

  <h2>Why is OP4Z mentioned in some docs but not in cadence's content?</h2>
  <p>
    OP4Z is the project where cadence's <code>./exc</code> automation system
    was originally built. Cadence is the public framework extraction. OP4Z
    keeps its specific RULES content, task helpers, and brand strings
    private; cadence ships the abstractions. Per the locked design, public
    cadence is ~60% reusable framework, ~40% scaffold templates.
  </p>

  <h2>Does cadence collect telemetry?</h2>
  <p>
    Cadence has <strong>opt-in</strong> telemetry. Off by default. On first
    run, you'll be prompted; if you opt in, anonymous usage events (command
    name, audit type, error type, cadence version, OS family) are recorded.
    No project paths, no user identifiers, no rule body content. v0.8 emits
    to <code>~/.config/cadence/telemetry.log</code> only — no real endpoint
    is wired yet. v1.0 will add the optional collector.
  </p>

  <h2>How do I license cadence?</h2>
  <p>
    Code is <a href="https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT">MIT</a>. Content
    (the standards docs, audit playbooks, this site) is
    <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">CC-BY 4.0</a>.
    You're free to fork, adapt, and ship in commercial software. Attribution
    is required for the content license; the code license has no
    attribution requirement.
  </p>
</Base>
